Based on these results, we propose a plausible PL working mechanism for the complexation between LERCDs and Ca2+ ions (
                        Fig. 6

                        ). The LERCDs after forming the complex with the Ca2+ ions, electrons from the conduction band of the LERCDs might be transferred to the empty 3d orbital of the Ca2+ ions. In this sense, a non-radiative electron transfer process may lead to the fluorescence quenching in the LERCDs. Previously, different authors have described the electron transfer processes for the PL quenching of fluorescent nanomaterials. For example, Sahoo et al. synthesized the CDs from the lychee waste and employed for the sensing of Fe3+ ions. Authors have studied the PL mechanism by static quenching where non-radiative aggregation leads to the PL quenching of the CDs [12]. B.A. Lakshmi et al. developed the ruthenium-quercetin nanoclusters (Ru-QC NCs) for the detection of Co2+ ions. The authors have explained the PL quenching of the Ru-QC NCs through the electron transfer process or the dynamic quenching [59].
